<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">The moving step. Block 1 broke the rock; today we ask where the pieces go.</p>
  <p>Erosion is what happens after weathering. Once a rock is broken down — by frost or roots or chemistry — something has to move the pieces. Today: the four erosion agents (water, wind, ice, gravity) and where each one dominates. In tropical monsoon Chennai, <strong>water dominates</strong>: rivers in the wet months, sheet wash on bare lateritic surfaces, wave erosion along the coast. Ice and frost-wedging are essentially absent. Wind matters mainly on the coast. Gravity (mass wasting) matters mainly in the Eastern Ghats foothills.</p>
  <p>The worked example today is <strong>Marina Beach</strong> — a 2005 / 2015 / 2025 satellite sequence. You'll see visible change across three timepoints. The point: erosion is happening here, now, on a beach you've walked on. Reading it is a learnable skill.</p>
</section>

